{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:48:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:48:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16723"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16723"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.2,0.07,0.32,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106305"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88773"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1546"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"7943"},{"type":"tags","id":"8105"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38883"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106305"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of asymptomatic hypopigmented patches on his trunk and arms. He migrated from India five years ago and works as a chef. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He reports that the patches feel numb when touched.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple well-defined hypopigmented patches with raised borders on his trunk and arms. The patches show reduced sensation to light touch and temperature. The ulnar and greater auricular nerves are thickened on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Split skin smear microscopy","Tuberculin skin test","Nerve conduction study","Skin biopsy","Antinuclear antibody test"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of leprosy (Hansen\u0027s disease), including hypopigmented patches with sensory loss and thickened peripheral nerves and living previously in an endemic country. Patients may also present with oedema, scaling, erythema nodosum leprosum and ulcers. Leprosy is a chronic infection by \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium leprae\u003C/em\u003E (\u003Cem\u003EM. leprae\u003C/em\u003E) and \u003Cem\u003EM. lepromatosis \u003C/em\u003Ecausing damage to the peripheral nerves. Though an ancient diseaese, it still is predominately found in India and Brazil, with new cases still occuring despite World Health Organisation intervention. The diagnosis requires confirmation through appropriate investigation before initiating treatment with multidrug therapy. Sadly though treatment is effective, the stigma of leprosy and the long-term neurological disabilities are ongoing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for confirming leprosy. Histopathological examination reveals characteristic granulomatous inflammatory changes and helps classify the disease into tuberculoid or lepromatous types, which guides treatment duration and choice of medications. While culturing \u003Cem\u003EM. leprae\u003C/em\u003E from biopsy specimens is nearly impossible, PCR testing can be performed on the tissue to confirm the diagnosis, which is particularly valuable in tuberculoid (paucibacillary) leprosy where acid-fast bacilli may be sparse or difficult to detect with conventional staining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplit skin smear microscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for detecting acid-fast bacilli and classifying leprosy into paucibacillary or multibacillary forms. However, it is less sensitive than biopsy and does not provide information about the tissue reaction pattern. In non-endemic areas, it is considered less definitive, and so a skin biopsy is often required for clinical, legal, and public health reasons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction study\u003C/strong\u003E can demonstrate nerve involvement in leprosy but is not the initial investigation of choice. It may be helpful in monitoring disease progression or detecting subclinical nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculin skin test\u003C/strong\u003E is not useful in diagnosing leprosy. While both diseases are caused by mycobacteria, the test does not differentiate between \u003Cem\u003EM. tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EM. leprae\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntinuclear antibody test\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for investigating autoimmune conditions that can cause hypopigmented patches, such as systemic lupus erythematosus. However, the presence of sensory loss and thickened nerves makes leprosy more likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Skin biopsy with histopathology is essential for confirming the diagnosis of leprosy and determining the type (tuberculoid vs lepromatous).","Loss of sensation in skin lesions is a cardinal feature of leprosy that should prompt investigation.","PCR testing on biopsy specimens is particularly valuable for confirming paucibacillary forms of leprosy where acid-fast bacilli may be sparse."],"references":["Chen KH, Lin CY, Su SB, Chen KT. Leprosy: A Review of Epidemiology, Clinical Diagnosis, and Management.  Journal of Tropical Medicine. 2022. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9273393/","White C, Franco-Paredes C. Leprosy in the 21st Century.  Clinical Microbiology Reviews. 2014.  Available at: https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/cmr.00079-13","Silva M et al. An update on leprosy immunopathogenesis: systematic review. Frontiers Immunology. 2024. Available at: https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/immunology/articles/10.3389/fimmu.2024.1416177/full"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88773"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88773"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T21:00:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T21:02:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106305"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T0